<subSubSection id="35D16528A60FFF8E4BDBFBFDFE804A9A" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="546" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" type="description">
<paragraph id="7D7436A3A60FFF8C4BDBFBFDFC294DAC" blockId="0.[685,1172,884,1730]" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4BDBFBFDFC614C71" bold="true" box="[709,957,1097,1118]" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Morphological Variation.</emphasis>
The specimens agree with the diagnosis given in 
<bibRefCitation id="195A4B52A60FFF8C4AAFFBD0FB904C56" author="Marquez" box="[945,1100,1124,1145]" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" pagination="491 - 523" refId="ref1439" refString="Marquez, J. 2003. Systematic revision of the genera Homalolinus Sharp, 1885 and Ehomalolinus Bierig, 1934 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Xantholinini). Zoologica Scripta 32: 491 - 523." type="journal article" year="2003">Márquez (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, except for the following characters: males (
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4D00FBCAFBF64CBC" box="[1054,1066,1150,1171]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">n</emphasis>
= 4) with total body length 16.0– 
<quantity id="BA339B46A60FFF8C4A8BFB2DFC334C81" box="[917,1007,1177,1198]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.77" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" unit="mm" value="17.7">17.7 mm</quantity>
; females (
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4D48FB2DFBBE4C81" box="[1110,1122,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">n</emphasis>
= 2) with total body length 
<quantity id="BA339B46A60FFF8C4A93FB00FBC24CE6" box="[909,1054,1203,1225]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.675" metricValueMax="1.73" metricValueMin="1.6199999999999999" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" unit="mm" value="16.75" valueMax="17.3" valueMin="16.2">16.2–17.3 mm</quantity>
; both males and females with scutellum nearly black, 
<specimenCount id="6BCDFD2AA60FFF8C4D23FB7AFB4F4CCC" box="[1085,1171,1230,1251]" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
with scutellum reddish brown; pro- and mesosternum reddish brown to brown; last two abdominal segments and genital segment orange. Aedeagus pear-shaped; total length 
<quantity id="BA339B46A60FFF8C4AA3FA8CFBC14D62" box="[957,1053,1336,1357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.32" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" unit="mm" value="1.32">1.32 mm</quantity>
; parameres asymmetrical; base of median lobe rounded; internal sac inconspicuous (
<figureCitation id="E5F02A26A60FFF8C4A92FADAFC354DAC" box="[908,1001,1389,1411]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[197,237,1661,1680]" captionTargetBox="[294,1072,192,1637]" captionTargetId="figure-1@1.[293,1072,192,1638]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–5. 1) Ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of the aedeagus of Homalolinus tlanchinolensis. Ventral view of the aedeagus of Homalolinus divisus: 2) Typical form; 3) From Guanajuato, Mexico; 4) From Guatemala; 5) From Honduras (redrawn from Márquez 2003). Scale bar = 1 mm." pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Fig. 1a–b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D7436A3A60FFF8E4BDBFA3CFE804A9A" blockId="0.[685,1172,884,1730]" lastBlockId="2.[151,638,194,693]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="546" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60FFF8C4BDBFA3CFC334DB2" authorityName="Marquez" authorityYear="2003" box="[709,1007,1416,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlanchinolensis">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4BDBFA3CFC334DB2" box="[709,1007,1416,1437]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Homalolinus tlanchinolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60FFF8C4D34FA3CFB484DB2" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1066,1172,1416,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4D34FA3CFB484DB2" box="[1066,1172,1416,1437]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">H. divisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sympatric in several places of 
<collectingRegion id="BF0FF841A60FFF8C4D09FA17FBBA4D97" box="[1047,1126,1443,1464]" country="Mexico" name="Hidalgo" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Hidalgo</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="BF0FF841A60FFF8C4BB3FA09FCD44DFD" box="[685,776,1469,1490]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="05DC7633A60FFF8C4A09FA09FCBA4DFD" box="[791,870,1469,1490]" name="Mexico" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Both species can be distinguished relatively easily because 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60FFF8C4AF7FA63FB484DC3" authorityName="Marquez" authorityYear="2003" box="[1001,1172,1495,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlanchinolensis">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4AF7FA63FB484DC3" box="[1001,1172,1495,1516]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">H. tlanchinolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the lateral area of the head with deep and dense punctures in the upper half and fine ones in the lower half, the scutellum is nearly black or at least reddish brown, the fifth visible abdominal segment is orange, and the base of the median lobe of the aedeagus is rounded, and the parameres are inserted near the middle of the median lobe (
<figureCitation id="E5F02A26A60FFF8C4BABF918FCFE4EEE" box="[693,802,1708,1730]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[197,237,1661,1680]" captionTargetBox="[294,1072,192,1637]" captionTargetId="figure-1@1.[293,1072,192,1638]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–5. 1) Ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of the aedeagus of Homalolinus tlanchinolensis. Ventral view of the aedeagus of Homalolinus divisus: 2) Typical form; 3) From Guanajuato, Mexico; 4) From Guatemala; 5) From Honduras (redrawn from Márquez 2003). Scale bar = 1 mm." pageId="0" pageNumber="544">Fig. 1a–b</figureCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60FFF8C4A23F918FC704EEE" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[829,940,1708,1729]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="544" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60FFF8C4A23F918FC704EEE" box="[829,940,1708,1729]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="544">H. divisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has deep and dense punctures in all lateral areas of the head, the scutellum is orange or red, the anterior half of the fifth visible abdominal segment is black and the posterior half is orange, and the base of the median lobe of the aedeagus is longer, less rounded than in 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60DFF8E484AFEF2FDC44974" authorityName="Marquez" authorityYear="2003" box="[340,536,326,347]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlanchinolensis">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60DFF8E484AFEF2FDC44974" box="[340,536,326,347]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">H. tlanchinolensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the parameres are inserted near the apical third of the median lobe (
<figureCitation id="E5F02A26A60DFF8E4853FEC8FE7249BE" box="[333,430,379,401]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[197,237,1661,1680]" captionTargetBox="[294,1072,192,1637]" captionTargetId="figure-1@1.[293,1072,192,1638]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–5. 1) Ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of the aedeagus of Homalolinus tlanchinolensis. Ventral view of the aedeagus of Homalolinus divisus: 2) Typical form; 3) From Guanajuato, Mexico; 4) From Guatemala; 5) From Honduras (redrawn from Márquez 2003). Scale bar = 1 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Figs. 2–5</figureCitation>
). The differences in the aedeagi from both species are evident in spite of the considerable variation observed in specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60DFF8E49E9FE7FFE8349CF" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[247,351,459,480]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60DFF8E49E9FE7FFE8349CF" box="[247,351,459,480]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">H. divisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from different localities of 
<collectingCountry id="05DC7633A60DFF8E4989FE52FF3949D4" box="[151,229,486,507]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="05DC7633A60DFF8E49E9FE52FEB949D4" box="[247,357,486,507]" name="Guatemala" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="05DC7633A60DFF8E48B8FE52FDD649D4" box="[422,522,486,507]" name="Honduras" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Honduras</collectingCountry>
; these differences do not correspond with differences in other morphological characters. Nevertheless, it is necessary to conduct a thorough re-analysis of many specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="BACB4D20A60DFF8E489AFDE4FE344A4A" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[388,488,592,613]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis id="4FBFEAB1A60DFF8E489AFDE4FE344A4A" box="[388,488,592,613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">H. divisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from different geographical areas to determine if the variation in the shape of the aedeagus corresponds to several distinct species.
</paragraph>
